1.	Introduction
The design of effective software systems requires a structured approach to requirements engineering, combining user-centered design with iterative development principles. This assignment applies Agile methodology, specifically user story modeling, to the development of a digital Battleship game.
Battleship, traditionally a two-player strategy game, presents an opportunity to explore how manual gameplay can be transformed into a robust, rule-driven software system. This work focuses on requirements elicitation, analysis, and specification, forming the foundation for future design and implementation phases within the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC).
2. Requirements Gathering via Interview
2.1 Interview Overview
A mock interview was conducted with a domain expert to extract core gameplay mechanics, user needs, and potential system constraints. This aligns with requirements elicitation techniques in software engineering, where stakeholder input informs system functionality.
2.2 Interview Questions and Responses
1. What is the primary objective of the game?
To locate and sink all opponent ships before losing one’s own fleet.
2. Who are the target users?
Primarily two players, ranging from beginners to experienced users. A digital system may also support single-player (AI) modes.
3. What are the essential game components?
•	Two grids per player (own board + tracking board) 
•	A fleet of ships of varying sizes 
•	Turn-based attack mechanism 
4. What rules govern ship placement?
Ships must be placed horizontally or vertically, within grid boundaries, and cannot overlap.
5. How does gameplay progress?
Players alternate turns selecting coordinates. The opponent provides feedback: hit or miss.
6. How is game success determined?
A player wins when all opponent ships are sunk.
7. What issues arise in the physical game?
•	Human error in tracking moves 
•	Miscommunication of hits/misses 
•	Incorrect ship placement 
8. What features are essential in a digital system?
•	Automated rule enforcement 
•	Real-time feedback 
•	Visual clarity 
•	Error prevention 
9. How should invalid actions be handled?
They should be prevented proactively, with immediate feedback.
10. What enhancements are possible in software?
•	AI opponent 
•	Visual and audio feedback 
•	Game analytics (accuracy, performance) 
2.3 Critical Analysis of Interview Findings
While the interview provides valuable foundational insights, several limitations and assumptions must be acknowledged:
•	Single-source bias: The requirements are derived from one expert, limiting diversity of perspectives. 
•	Implicit assumptions: The model assumes a two-player system, potentially restricting scalability to AI or multiplayer modes. 
•	Lack of edge-case discussion: Exceptional scenarios (e.g., disconnections, invalid repeated inputs) were not explored. 
From a design perspective, the findings emphasize:
•	Functional accuracy through strict rule enforcement 
•	Usability aligned with HCI principles (minimizing cognitive load) 
•	Error prevention, a core usability heuristic (Nielsen, 1994) 
These insights inform both functional and non-functional requirements.
3. Requirements Specification
3.1 Functional Requirements
The system shall:
•	Allow players to place ships according to defined rules 
•	Enable turn-based coordinate selection 
•	Provide immediate feedback (hit/miss/sunk) 
•	Track all player actions 
•	Detect win conditions 
•	Allow game restart
3.2 Non-Functional Requirements
To ensure system quality, the following constraints are defined:
Usability
•	New users should understand gameplay within 5 minutes 
•	Interface must be intuitive and visually clear 
Performance
•	System response time ≤ 1 second per action 
Reliability
•	Game state must persist accurately throughout gameplay 
Scalability
•	System should support future extensions (e.g., AI, multiplayer) 
Security 
•	Prevent manipulation of game state (e.g., duplicate moves)









4. User Stories with Acceptance Criteria
User stories are structured according to Agile principles (Beck et al., 2001), forming an initial product backlog.
(a)	High Priority User Stories (Core Gameplay)
User Story 1: Ship Placement
As a player, I want to place ships on a grid so that I can prepare for gameplay.
Acceptance Criteria:
•	Ships can only be placed horizontally or vertically 
•	Ships cannot overlap 
•	Ships must remain within grid boundaries 
•	The system confirms valid placement before proceeding
User Story 2: Attack Mechanism
As a player, I want to select coordinates to attack so that I can locate opponent ships.
Acceptance Criteria:
•	Player can select exactly one coordinate per turn 
•	System responds within ≤1 second 
•	Result is displayed as “Hit” or “Miss” 
•	Selected coordinate cannot be reused
User Story 3: Turn Management
As a player, I want turns to alternate automatically so that gameplay is fair.
Acceptance Criteria:
•	Only one player is active at a time 
•	System clearly displays active player 
•	Turn switches only after valid move
(b)	Medium Priority (Game Feedback & Tracking)
User Story 4: Feedback System
As a player, I want immediate feedback so that I understand the result of my actions.
Acceptance Criteria:
•	“Hit” or “Miss” displayed within ≤1 second 
•	“Ship Sunk” notification displayed when applicable 
•	Feedback is visually distinct
User Story 5: Tracking Grid
As a player, I want a tracking grid so that I can monitor my previous moves.
Acceptance Criteria:
•	All moves are recorded and visible 
•	Hits and misses are clearly distinguished 
•	Duplicate selections are prevented
(c)	Low Priority (Enhancements)
User Story 6: Game Restart
As a player, I want to restart the game so that I can play again.
Acceptance Criteria:
•	Restart resets all game data 
•	Game returns to initial setup state
User Story 7: User Guidance
As a new player, I want instructions so that I can learn the game quickly.
Acceptance Criteria:
•	Instructions available before gameplay 
•	Instructions explain rules and controls clearly 
5. Edge Cases and Constraints
To ensure robustness, the system must handle:
•	Duplicate coordinate selection attempts 
•	Invalid ship placements 
•	Rapid repeated inputs (debouncing required) 
•	Interrupted gameplay sessions 
These considerations align with defensive design principles in software engineering.

6. System Perspective (High-Level Design)
The system can be conceptualized as three main components:
1.	User Interface Layer 
o	Displays grids and feedback 
o	Handles user interaction 
2.	Game Logic Engine 
o	Enforces rules 
o	Processes moves 
o	Determines outcomes 
3.	State Management System 
o	Tracks game progress 
o	Stores ship positions and attack history 
This modular approach supports maintainability and future scalability.
7. Alignment with Agile and SDLC
The defined user stories form the initial product backlog, which can be implemented iteratively through Agile sprints:
•	Sprint 1: Core gameplay (placement, attack, turns) 
•	Sprint 2: Feedback and tracking 
•	Sprint 3: Enhancements and UI improvements 
This iterative model supports continuous testing, validation, and refinement.
8. Conclusion
This analysis demonstrates the transformation of a traditional board game into a structured software system through rigorous requirements engineering. By integrating user-centered design, Agile principles, and system-level thinking, the proposed solution ensures both functional correctness and a high-quality user experience.
The inclusion of prioritized user stories, measurable acceptance criteria, and non-functional requirements establishes a strong foundation for implementation, testing, and future system expansion.
 
